[32m│[0m ## Analysis Results                                                          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ### Key Findings:                                                            [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m **All GET requests with URL parameters returned identical responses** - none [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m of the URL parameters (`name`, `input`, `q`, `search`) are being processed   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m when sent via GET request. They all show:                                    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ```javascript                                                                [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m <script> var name = ""; document.write('Hello ' + name); </script>           [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ```                                                                          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m The `name` variable remains **empty string** in all cases, regardless of     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m which parameter or value was sent in the URL.                                [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ### Critical Observations:                                                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 1. **URL Parameters Are Ignored**: The application does NOT process URL      [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m parameters (GET) - it only processes POST body parameters based on the form  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m method `method="post"`                                                       [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 2. **The Vulnerability Point**: The JavaScript code shows:                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m    - `var name = "";` - currently empty                                      [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m    - `document.write('Hello ' + name);` - string concatenation vulnerability [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m    - This suggests the `name` parameter from POST requests gets injected     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m into this JavaScript variable                                                [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 3. **No HTML Encoding**: The value appears to be directly injected into      [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m JavaScript without proper escaping, making it vulnerable to XSS if we can    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m control the content                                                          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 4. **Form Behavior**: The HTML form shows:                                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m    ```html                                                                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m    <form class="box-form" method="post">                                     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m        <textarea name=name cols=50 rows=20 placeholder="Enter your           [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m name..."></textarea>                                                         [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m        <input type=submit value="Submit">                                    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m    </form>                                                                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m    ```                                                                       [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m    This confirms the application expects POST requests with a `name`         [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m parameter.                                                                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m ### Conclusion:                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m **GET parameters are NOT processed** - the application is designed to only   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m accept POST body parameters. The `name` parameter must be sent via POST      [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m request body (as form data) to be reflected in the JavaScript code. This is  [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m why previous POST attempts showed the value being injected into the          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m JavaScript variable, while GET requests show an empty string.                [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m **Next Step**: We need to focus on POST requests with the `name` parameter   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m to exploit the XSS vulnerability in the JavaScript context.                  [32m│[0m
